		<h1>MORAINE LAKE</h1>
		<p>
			<strong>Moraine Lake</strong>, located in Banff National Park in Alberta, Canada, is one of the most breathtaking natural wonders in the world. Nestled in the Valley of the Ten Peaks, the lake is surrounded by towering mountains, lush forests, and glacial streams that give it an ethereal beauty. Its vibrant turquoise waters, a result of light refracting off rock flour deposited by surrounding glaciers, make it one of the most photographed spots in the Canadian Rockies. Moraine Lake sits at an elevation of 1,884 meters (6,181 feet) and spans an area of about 50 hectares (120 acres), offering visitors a serene and picturesque retreat. Popular activities include hiking, canoeing, and photography, with trails such as the Rockpile Trail providing panoramic views of the lake and its majestic backdrop. The lake is a seasonal attraction, accessible during the warmer months when snow and ice recede, allowing its vibrant colors to shine. Known as a symbol of Canada’s natural heritage, it has been featured on the country’s twenty-dollar bill and attracts nature lovers from around the globe. Moraine Lake remains a must-visit destination for those seeking tranquility and the raw beauty of the Rockies.
		</p>
